So that’s my brain on the booster shot,

In the space of a week after the Fisk money dried up, departments split apart, journals shut down, people got radicalized in various ways and found their new off-campus audiences / echo chambers… w the rest of us saying “I had no idea. I don’t even know where their building is.”

And the third axis of division was about whether the discipline should be basically *anti*-travel, for carbon emissions reasons that then got mixed up with arguments about travel during COVID. 

And all this stuff exploded out into the open at once on social media.

People who worked on unpleasant topics, such as documenting travel to post-genocide mass graves, said they couldn’t get their work published in the journal anymore. It had become too commercial and nice.

Second divide was over the flagship journal, which had gradually become a wold-leading site for literary non-fiction travel writing. The publisher of the journal was very happy with this—lots of off-campus individual subscribers. But…

They were very different from other dive charts, and one side said they reflected an alternative progressive epistemology, while the other tried to prove that they just used different units and ran equipment & bodies closer to the edge of tolerance.

In real time on social media. So I got to learn all about the fractures in this discipline I had never heard of. 

One fracture was very specific and narrow, and everyone knew that, but it was bitter: whether to use old Soviet dive charts in research about scuba diving.

Wild (booster-shot-induced) dream: there was a whole academic discipline I had never heard of called Travel Studies. It’s growth had been supported by Wilson Fisk, whose support dried up for obvious reasons.

W/o the money to solve problems, the discipline went into meltdown…
